in Florida.</i>

1044
00:38:38,150 --> 00:38:41,120
<i>Vicky had finished her MBA,
which I paid for.</i>

1045
00:38:41,153 --> 00:38:43,423
<i>Big Lola had plans
to open up a dungeon.</i>

1046
00:38:43,457 --> 00:38:46,226
<i>But we could always do better.</i>

1047
00:38:46,260 --> 00:38:48,829
Hey. Don't be nervous, okay?

1048
00:38:48,862 --> 00:38:51,565
I have the perfect
first job for you.

1049
00:38:51,598 --> 00:38:52,232
Don't worry.

1050
00:38:52,266 --> 00:38:54,835
There's none of that. Okay?

1051
00:38:54,868 --> 00:38:56,470
Ten minutes,
and you'll walk away

1052
00:38:56,503 --> 00:38:57,069
with two grand
in your pocket.

1053
00:38:57,103 --> 00:38:59,071
Okay, baby. We got you.

1054
00:38:59,105 --> 00:38:59,806
Looking good, mama.

1055
00:38:59,840 --> 00:39:02,174
Smile.

1056
00:39:03,142 --> 00:39:05,279
Two grand in 10 minutes?

1057
00:39:05,312 --> 00:39:06,847
- What job is that?
- "Halloweenie."

1058
00:39:06,880 --> 00:39:07,814
That's my client.

1059
00:39:07,848 --> 00:39:09,316
Was your client.

1060
00:39:09,349 --> 00:39:11,318
With your old ass.

1061
00:39:11,351 --> 00:39:12,753
Look, he requested
someone new, okay?

1062
00:39:12,786 --> 00:39:14,454
Happens all the time.
Don't take it personal.

1063
00:39:15,856 --> 00:39:17,056
[♪♪]

1064
00:39:22,128 --> 00:39:24,598
She is going to make us
a lot of money.

1065
00:39:24,631 --> 00:39:27,401
[Anna] We're gonna make her
a lot of money.

1066
00:39:27,434 --> 00:39:31,538
We're gonna give her a life
she never thought possible.

1067
00:39:31,572 --> 00:39:32,773
I like her.

1068
00:39:32,806 --> 00:39:34,775
She reminds me of me.

1069
00:39:34,808 --> 00:39:36,610
[chuckles]

1070
00:39:36,643 --> 00:39:38,144
[♪♪]

1071
00:39:38,177 --> 00:39:40,847
[eerie score plays]

1072
00:39:40,881 --> 00:39:42,549
Hello?

1073
00:39:42,583 --> 00:39:44,116
Is anyone there?

1074
00:39:44,150 --> 00:39:47,220
[eerie music plays]

1075
00:39:48,889 --> 00:39:49,856
Oh, gosh!

1076
00:39:49,890 --> 00:39:51,858
It's so creepy

1077
00:39:51,892 --> 00:39:52,859
and I'm all alone!

1078
00:39:52,893 --> 00:39:55,596
What's going on?

1079
00:39:55,629 --> 00:39:56,730
Someone?

1080
00:39:56,763 --> 00:39:57,163
Anyone?

1081
00:39:57,196 --> 00:40:00,601
I'm so scared!

1082
00:40:00,634 --> 00:40:04,905
I vant to suck
your bloo-oo-ood!

1083
00:40:04,938 --> 00:40:06,473
[Anna] <i>Carlton Wellings.</i>

1084
00:40:06,506 --> 00:40:07,641
<i>Age 76.</i>

1085
00:40:07,674 --> 00:40:09,209
<i>He made his fortune
in early horror movies.</i>

1086
00:40:09,242 --> 00:40:11,143
<i>Net worth: 200 million.</i>

1087
00:40:11,177 --> 00:40:12,279
<i>Alias: Halloweenie.</i>

1088
00:40:12,312 --> 00:40:16,249
[shrieking theatrically]

1089
00:40:20,220 --> 00:40:22,589
Well?

1090
00:40:22,623 --> 00:40:23,590
How was it?

1091
00:40:23,624 --> 00:40:25,258
Good, I think.

1092
00:40:26,226 --> 00:40:27,260
Lunch is on you, Spokane.

1093
00:40:27,294 --> 00:40:29,529
[gasps]

1094
00:40:33,967 --> 00:40:35,802
I, uh, never forget a face...

1095
00:40:37,437 --> 00:40:40,641
...especially one that almost
put me in the hospital.

1096
00:40:40,674 --> 00:40:42,776
I didn't catch your name.
Owen.

1097
00:40:42,809 --> 00:40:43,043
Anna. Hi.

1098
00:40:43,076 --> 00:40:45,278
Hi.

1099
00:40:45,312 --> 00:40:47,414
Is that one yours?

1100
00:40:47,447 --> 00:40:49,416
- Yeah.
- She looks comfortable.

1101
00:40:49,449 --> 00:40:50,384
How long did that take?

1102
00:40:50,417 --> 00:40:53,220
Five years? Six, maybe.

1103
00:40:53,253 --> 00:40:55,422
My wife used to ride.

1104
00:40:55,455 --> 00:40:56,323
Before she passed,

1105
00:40:56,356 --> 00:40:59,191
I promised her
I'd get Emma into it.

1106
00:40:59,226 --> 00:41:02,229
My kid has no interest
in doing what Mom wanted.

1107
00:41:02,262 --> 00:41:04,231
She wants to play the violin.

1108
00:41:04,264 --> 00:41:06,667
What, she can't do both?

1109
00:41:06,700 --> 00:41:07,267
You ever heard an 8-year-old
play the violin?

1110
00:41:07,300 --> 00:41:09,970
[laughs]

1111
00:41:10,003 --> 00:41:13,407
Well, uh... here.

1112
00:41:13,440 --> 00:41:14,274
If you have any questions,

1113
00:41:14,307 --> 00:41:16,677
Mia could always
give Emma some pointers.

1114
00:41:16,710 --> 00:41:19,446
By the way, this is not
me hitting on you.

1115
00:41:19,479 --> 00:41:21,848
Oh, by the way,
that would be fine if it was.

1116
00:41:24,017 --> 00:41:26,286
[phone rings]

1117
00:41:26,319 --> 00:41:28,789
Sorry, I need to get this.

1118
00:41:28,822 --> 00:41:29,823
Sure.

1119
00:41:30,357 --> 00:41:32,292
Mark, how are you?

1120
00:41:32,325 --> 00:41:34,594
Are you sure you don't
want to reschedule?

1121
00:41:38,832 --> 00:41:39,866
[Mia screams]

1122
00:41:39,900 --> 00:41:41,334
Mia! Mia, are you okay?

1123
00:41:41,368 --> 00:41:43,737
Baby, are you okay?

1124
00:41:44,771 --> 00:41:45,972
[Mia] Mom...

1125
00:41:46,006 --> 00:41:47,808
Hey, hey. What's wrong, baby?
What's wrong?

1126
00:41:47,841 --> 00:41:48,275
Hey, you okay?

1127
00:41:48,308 --> 00:41:50,677
Is it your ankle?

1128
00:41:50,711 --> 00:41:51,978
Okay, here.
Let me help you up.

1129
00:41:52,012 --> 00:41:53,346
Come on.

1130
00:41:53,380 --> 00:41:54,514
Grab onto me, baby.

1131
00:41:54,548 --> 00:41:55,515
[Mia] It really hurts.

1132
00:41:55,549 --> 00:41:57,551
[Anna] Okay, apply
more pressure on me, baby.

1133
00:41:57,584 --> 00:42:01,354
Oh, well, now she hates horses.
Lovely.

1134
00:42:01,388 --> 00:42:03,957
It's a good thing
it's just a sprained ankle.

1135
00:42:03,990 --> 00:42:04,958
Mm.

1136
00:42:04,991 --> 00:42:06,593
Take a look.

1137
00:42:06,626 --> 00:42:07,561
Who's Meredith Prisker,

1138
00:42:07,594 --> 00:42:09,696
and why is she a third
of my party budget?

1139
00:42:09,730 --> 00:42:10,464
You need a DJ.

1140
00:42:10,497 --> 00:42:12,632
For seven grand,
I'll be the DJ.

1141
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:15,736
- Ow.
- [phone rings]

1142
00:42:18,004 --> 00:42:18,972
This is Anna.

1143
00:42:19,005 --> 00:42:20,006
Anna, it's Dymitri.

1144
00:42:20,040 --> 00:42:20,974
<i>Dymitri.</i>

1145
00:42:21,007 --> 00:42:21,641
How are you?

1146
00:42:21,675 --> 00:42:25,011
<i>Dymitri Polokov, age 49.</i>

1147
00:42:25,045 --> 00:42:26,313
<i>Heir to an oil fortune</i>

1148
00:42:26,346 --> 00:42:26,980
<i>and son of a prominent member
of the Russian mob.</i>

1149
00:42:27,013 --> 00:42:29,382
<i>Net worth: 3.6 billion.</i>

1150
00:42:29,416 --> 00:42:31,351
<i>Alias: The Russian James Bond.</i>

1151
00:42:31,384 --> 00:42:33,353
Is everything all right?

1152
00:42:33,386 --> 00:42:34,621
<i>Everything is very good.</i>

1153
00:42:34,654 --> 00:42:35,522
So busy.

1154
00:42:35,555 --> 00:42:37,324
I need to cancel with Vicky.

1155
00:42:37,357 --> 00:42:39,392
She'll be sorry to hear that.

1156
00:42:39,426 --> 00:42:40,360
Give me a call
when things calm down.

1157
00:42:43,630 --> 00:42:44,498
What?

1158
00:42:44,531 --> 00:42:46,433
That was my third cancellation
for Vicky

1159
00:42:46,466 --> 00:42:47,734
in the past few days.

1160
00:42:47,768 --> 00:42:49,002
Third.

1161
00:42:49,035 --> 00:42:49,970
Who?

1162
00:42:50,003 --> 00:42:52,672
Strikeout, Cowboy,
and Russian James Bond.

1163
00:42:53,807 --> 00:42:54,908
Hi, Anna.

1164
00:42:54,941 --> 00:42:55,842
<i>Hey, Vicky.</i>

1165
00:42:55,876 --> 00:42:57,577
Sorry to call so late.
You have a minute?

1166
00:42:57,611 --> 00:42:59,312
- Yeah, of course.
- Well, I'm sorry

1167
00:42:59,346 --> 00:43:00,781
to do this to you,
but I, uh...

1168
00:43:00,814 --> 00:43:03,083
I have another cancellation
for you.

1169
00:43:03,116 --> 00:43:04,351
That's too bad.

1170
00:43:04,384 --> 00:43:05,752
<i>You know, maybe I should</i>

1171
00:43:05,786 --> 00:43:07,454
just take a vacation
for a few days.

1172
00:43:07,487 --> 00:43:08,989
[Anna]
<i>It's never a coincidence</i>

1173
00:43:09,022 --> 00:43:11,591
<i>when clients start canceling
one after the other...</i>

1174
00:43:11,625 --> 00:43:13,560
<i>especially when
they've booked the same girl</i>

1175
00:43:13,593 --> 00:43:14,194
<i>and don't reschedule.</i>

1176
00:43:14,228 --> 00:43:16,429
<i>I knew what was up.</i>

1177
00:43:16,463 --> 00:43:18,498
A vacation?
Yeah, you know what?

1178
00:43:18,532 --> 00:43:20,534
<i>You might as well, right?</i>

1179
00:43:24,805 --> 00:43:26,406
What's wrong?

1180
00:43:26,439 --> 00:43:28,775
She was my first girl.

1181
00:43:28,809 --> 00:43:30,477
My best girl.

1182
00:43:30,510 --> 00:43:31,178
We were in this
from the beginning

1183
00:43:31,212 --> 00:43:32,112
and this is what she does to me?

1184
00:43:32,145 --> 00:43:36,349
Well, she's not as young
as she used to be.

1185
00:43:36,383 --> 00:43:38,451
I'm sure she has her reasons.

1186
00:43:38,485 --> 00:43:40,654
I put her through college.

1187
00:43:40,687 --> 00:43:41,521
Okay.

1188
00:43:41,555 --> 00:43:43,456
Don't do anything crazy.

1189
00:43:44,524 --> 00:43:46,827
I need to make a point.

1190
00:43:46,860 --> 00:43:48,328
I mean, who the hell
does she think she is?

1191
00:43:56,970 --> 00:43:58,471
[Anna] <i>I was the co-signer
on Vicky's first condo</i>

1192
00:43:58,505 --> 00:44:00,140
<i>and had a set of back-up keys.</i>

1193
00:44:00,173 --> 00:44:02,843
<i>When I knew she'd be out,</i>

1194
00:44:02,876 --> 00:44:04,344
<i>I let myself in.</i>

1195
00:44:10,083 --> 00:44:11,184
<i>Just what I thought.</i>

1196
00:44:11,219 --> 00:44:12,953
<i>She was getting clients
to cancel with me,</i>

1197
00:44:12,986 --> 00:44:14,020
<i>seeing them anyway,</i>

1198
00:44:14,054 --> 00:44:15,488
<i>and taking all the money
for herself...</i>

1199
00:44:15,522 --> 00:44:16,156
<i>the classic workaround.</i>

1200
00:44:16,189 --> 00:44:17,357
<i>Bitch.</i>

1201
00:44:27,067 --> 00:44:28,501
<i>She also owed me 16 grand.</i>

1202
00:44:29,202 --> 00:44:32,105
<i>Rule number three?</i>

1203
00:44:32,138 --> 00:44:33,907
<i>Don't mess with my money.</i>

1204
00:44:36,476 --> 00:44:39,112
[phone rings]

1205
00:44:39,145 --> 00:44:40,113
This is Anna.

1206
00:44:40,146 --> 00:44:40,180
[line hangs up]

1207
00:44:42,682 --> 00:44:45,051
[dial tone buzzes]

1208
00:44:51,057 --> 00:44:52,025
All right, honey.

1209
00:44:52,058 --> 00:44:53,460
Lunch is served.

1210
00:44:53,493 --> 00:44:55,662
There you go. Make room.

1211
00:44:57,564 --> 00:44:59,633
- ["wind" breaks]
- Oh!

1212
00:44:59,666 --> 00:45:01,067
- [laughing]
- What?

1213
00:45:03,970 --> 00:45:04,938
Very funny.

1214
00:45:06,006 --> 00:45:07,040
Out.

1215
00:45:07,073 --> 00:45:08,675
I need to talk to Letty.

1216
00:45:12,679 --> 00:45:14,581
If you want to know
about your party,

1217
00:45:14,614 --> 00:45:15,482
mm, I know nothing.

1218
00:45:15,515 --> 00:45:19,552
[stammers] No. Uh...

1219
00:45:19,586 --> 00:45:21,521
Is Mom okay?

1220
00:45:21,554 --> 00:45:22,622
How do you mean?

1221
00:45:22,656 --> 00:45:27,460
It just seems like maybe
she's having money problems

1222
00:45:27,494 --> 00:45:28,795
or something?

1223
00:45:28,828 --> 00:45:31,831
Your mother is always
on top of her money.

1224
00:45:31,865 --> 00:45:33,533
You won't ever
have to worry about that.

1225
00:45:33,566 --> 00:45:35,835
'Kay?

1226
00:45:37,037 --> 00:45:38,772
Yeah. Yeah.

1227
00:45:38,805 --> 00:45:40,573
But, like, it just seems weird

1228
00:45:40,607 --> 00:45:42,243
that she always has
so much cash laying around

1229
00:45:42,276 --> 00:45:44,511
and doesn't like banks.

1230
00:45:44,544 --> 00:45:45,779
Like, I know about the salon,

1231
00:45:45,812 --> 00:45:47,814
but what
is "head hunting"?

1232
00:45:47,847 --> 00:45:52,219
So, your mother matches
her clients with employers

1233
00:45:52,253 --> 00:45:53,553
based on need and talent.

1234
00:45:56,656 --> 00:45:57,490
Anna's fine.

1235
00:45:57,524 --> 00:45:59,793
I promise.

1236
00:45:59,826 --> 00:46:01,728
Okay?

1237
00:46:02,963 --> 00:46:03,863
Okay.

1238
00:46:08,101 --> 00:46:09,135
Sorry.

1239
00:46:09,169 --> 00:46:11,838
Sorry. You know how I am.

1240
00:46:11,871 --> 00:46:12,572
I do now.

1241
00:46:12,605 --> 00:46:14,541
What's that
supposed to mean?

1242
00:46:14,574 --> 00:46:17,010
Sit.

1243
00:46:19,713 --> 00:46:21,948
What's going on?

1244
00:46:21,982 --> 00:46:24,484
You tell me.

1245
00:46:29,323 --> 00:46:32,158
[thud]

1246
00:46:35,662 --> 00:46:39,733
You were one of
my first "A"-list girls.

1247
00:46:39,766 --> 00:46:42,303
I hired you
when you were nothing.

1248
00:46:42,336 --> 00:46:44,070
I glammed you up.

1249
00:46:44,104 --> 00:46:44,604
I got you clients.

1250
00:46:44,637 --> 00:46:47,040
I treated you fair.

1251
00:46:47,073 --> 00:46:48,641
I made sure
you became somebody.

1252
00:46:48,675 --> 00:46:51,177
Why'd you burn me?

1253
00:46:51,212 --> 00:46:52,579
Anna, look, I can explain.

1254
00:46:52,612 --> 00:46:53,747
You know what?

1255
00:46:54,714 --> 00:46:56,217
I don't want to hear it.

1256
00:46:56,250 --> 00:46:57,318
Here's what's about to happen.

1257
00:46:57,351 --> 00:46:59,552
I took my cut,
fair and square.

1258
00:46:59,586 --> 00:47:01,654
The rest of your money's
in the bag.

1259
00:47:01,688 --> 00:47:03,656
From here on out,

1260
00:47:03,690 --> 00:47:05,091
you and me,

1261
00:47:05,125 --> 00:47:06,760
we're done.

1262
00:47:08,362 --> 00:47:12,266
Go with them.

1263
00:47:12,299 --> 00:47:12,799
Where?

1264
00:47:12,832 --> 00:47:13,367
Don't make a scene.

1265
00:47:13,401 --> 00:47:16,102
Have a little dignity.

1266
00:47:16,136 --> 00:47:17,037
Anna, please,
just let me explain.

1267
00:47:17,070 --> 00:47:19,340
I should've left you
and your cheap shoes

1268
00:47:19,373 --> 00:47:21,074
where I found you.

1269
00:47:21,107 --> 00:47:22,108
[Vicky sobs]

1270
00:47:22,142 --> 00:47:23,176
No, please.

1271
00:47:23,210 --> 00:47:25,078
Get out.

1272
00:47:26,179 --> 00:47:29,082
[♪♪]

1273
00:47:36,856 --> 00:47:37,657
That looked dramatic.

1274
00:47:37,690 --> 00:47:39,559
[forced chuckle]

1275
00:47:42,195 --> 00:47:43,330
Do tell.

1276
00:47:56,743 --> 00:47:58,379
No...

1277
00:47:58,412 --> 00:47:59,380
-Come on.

1278
00:47:59,413 --> 00:48:01,681
Let's go.

1279
00:48:01,714 --> 00:48:03,116
Come on!

1280
00:48:05,386 --> 00:48:05,785
Take the money.

1281
00:48:05,819 --> 00:48:06,320
Don't kill me.

1282
00:48:06,353 --> 00:48:07,388
Shut up and listen.

1283
00:48:07,421 --> 00:48:09,889
Take the money.

1284
00:48:09,923 --> 00:48:11,624
The airport's a mile that way.

1285
00:48:11,658 --> 00:48:13,860
Get on a plane
and don't come back,

1286
00:48:13,893 --> 00:48:16,263
'cause, if you do,

1287
00:48:16,297 --> 00:48:16,596
there's gonna be a problem.

1288
00:48:22,702 --> 00:48:24,737
[door rumbles and thuds]

1289
00:48:24,771 --> 00:48:27,140
[♪♪]

1290
00:48:30,444 --> 00:48:31,778
I think you made your point.

1291
00:48:31,811 --> 00:48:34,348
Oh, I did.

1292
00:48:34,381 --> 00:48:35,416
[both laughing]

1293
00:48:35,449 --> 00:48:37,384
[Anna] <i>Being a madam
is a lonely life,</i>

1294
00:48:37,418 --> 00:48:38,852
<i>everyone's your enemy,</i>

1295
00:48:38,885 --> 00:48:40,787
<i>but we were equals.</i>

1296
00:48:40,820 --> 00:48:42,755
That night,
Simone and I became friends.

1297
00:48:42,789 --> 00:48:44,891
<i>By closing time, we agreed</i>

1298
00:48:44,924 --> 00:48:47,193
<i>that if one of my regulars
was traveling to Europe,</i>

1299
00:48:47,228 --> 00:48:49,829
<i>Simone would handle it
and vice versa.</i>

1300
00:48:49,863 --> 00:48:50,797
<i>With Simone backing me up,</i>

1301
00:48:50,830 --> 00:48:53,234
<i>I was Don Corleone.</i>

1302
00:48:54,167 --> 00:48:56,202
[Owen]
So, what do you do for fun?

1303
00:48:56,237 --> 00:48:57,837
I took the kids to Orlando
last summer.

1304
00:48:57,871 --> 00:48:58,705
We did all the parks.

1305
00:48:58,738 --> 00:49:00,140
And then last year,
we went skiing.

1306
00:49:00,173 --> 00:49:02,876
Now I'm a working mom
and that feels right.

1307
00:49:02,909 --> 00:49:04,677
I like being valuable to people.

1308
00:49:04,711 --> 00:49:05,778
And I have
a pretty good group of girls,

1309
00:49:05,812 --> 00:49:07,780
for the most part.

1310
00:49:07,814 --> 00:49:09,416
- At the salon?
- Right.

1311
00:49:09,450 --> 00:49:11,318
At the salon, yes.

1312
00:49:12,319 --> 00:49:14,087
Well...

1313
00:49:14,120 --> 00:49:15,456
here we are.

1314
00:49:15,489 --> 00:49:16,689
What do you think?

1315
00:49:16,723 --> 00:49:18,191
I like it.

1316
00:49:18,225 --> 00:49:19,460
I couldn't tell you why,
but I... I do.

1317
00:49:19,493 --> 00:49:21,761
Thanks.

1318
00:49:21,794 --> 00:49:25,332
So you did this,
from top to bottom?

1319
00:49:25,366 --> 00:49:26,467
And everything in between.

1320
00:49:26,500 --> 00:49:28,435
Did I impress you?

1321
00:49:28,469 --> 00:49:30,204
Maybe.

1322
00:49:30,237 --> 00:49:31,671
[chuckles]

1323
00:49:32,506 --> 00:49:35,008
This one is Emma's favorite.

1324
00:49:35,041 --> 00:49:36,910
Every time we drive past,
she points at it,

1325
00:49:36,943 --> 00:49:38,711
she says,
"That's Daddy's building."

1326
00:49:38,745 --> 00:49:40,780
That's pretty cool, you know?

1327
00:49:40,813 --> 00:49:43,484
When your kid's proud of you.

1328
00:49:43,517 --> 00:49:47,321
And hopefully, one day,
the grandkids'll know about it.

1329
00:49:47,354 --> 00:49:49,323
That's legacy.

1330
00:49:50,524 --> 00:49:53,494
Wow.

1331
00:49:53,527 --> 00:49:55,828
I really did impress you.

1332
00:49:56,829 --> 00:49:58,432
Want to take a closer look?

1333
00:49:58,465 --> 00:49:59,366
Yeah.

1334
00:50:02,769 --> 00:50:05,004
This is me.

1335
00:50:05,038 --> 00:50:08,509
We, uh,
we should do this again.

1336
00:50:08,542 --> 00:50:09,943
I'd invite you over,

1337
00:50:09,976 --> 00:50:12,045
but my son has just discovered
whoopee cushions

1338
00:50:12,078 --> 00:50:13,813
and you'd be a perfect target.

1339
00:50:13,846 --> 00:50:15,181
Well, next time.

1340
00:50:15,216 --> 00:50:16,250
Yeah.

1341
00:50:19,420 --> 00:50:20,454
Sorry.

1342
00:50:20,487 --> 00:50:21,754
It's, uh...

1343
00:50:21,788 --> 00:50:22,789
it's been a while.

1344
00:50:22,822 --> 00:50:25,992
I'm willing to give it a shot.

1345
00:50:26,893 --> 00:50:29,729
[♪♪]

1346
00:50:41,375 --> 00:50:42,276
Goodnight.

1347
00:50:43,510 --> 00:50:45,379
Goodnight.

1348
00:50:50,850 --> 00:50:51,751
[phone rings]

1349
00:50:54,954 --> 00:50:56,357
This is Anna.

1350
00:50:56,390 --> 00:50:57,790
[line hangs up]

1351
00:50:57,824 --> 00:51:00,461
[dial tone buzzing]

1352
00:51:00,494 --> 00:51:02,363
[Anna] <i>Dropped calls
mean one of two things...</i>

1353
00:51:02,396 --> 00:51:04,063
<i>one, bad service.</i>

1354
00:51:04,097 --> 00:51:06,300
<i>Two, the Feds were onto me.</i>

1355
00:51:06,333 --> 00:51:08,435
<i>Now, I'd been careful,
but in the back of my mind,</i>

1356
00:51:08,469 --> 00:51:10,237
<i>I worried if
someone might be listening.</i>

1357
00:51:10,271 --> 00:51:11,070
Mom?

1358
00:51:11,104 --> 00:51:13,906
Is everything okay?

1359
00:51:13,940 --> 00:51:15,875
Everything's fine.

1360
00:51:15,908 --> 00:51:17,478
Would you tell me
if it wasn't?

1361
00:51:17,511 --> 00:51:19,178
[♪♪]

1362
00:51:24,251 --> 00:51:25,885
[dance music thumping]

1363
00:51:25,918 --> 00:51:28,555
[♪♪]

1364
00:51:29,856 --> 00:51:34,261
♪ It's all play
or not at all ♪

1365
00:51:34,295 --> 00:51:35,995
♪ If you wanna
dance, dance, dance... ♪

1366
00:51:36,029 --> 00:51:36,829
Hello, girls!

1367
00:51:36,863 --> 00:51:39,165
How are you?

1368
00:51:39,198 --> 00:51:41,167
Cake and presents
in five minutes.

1369
00:51:42,135 --> 00:51:43,470
What's with the attitude?

1370
00:51:43,504 --> 00:51:45,372
What's with your attitude?

1371
00:51:45,406 --> 00:51:48,409
You're the one
always sneaking around.

1372
00:51:48,442 --> 00:51:50,411
I'm gonna ignore that.

1373
00:51:50,444 --> 00:51:51,944
Presents. Go.

1374
00:51:53,012 --> 00:51:55,948
Hey, wow. This party...

1375
00:51:55,982 --> 00:51:57,217
how much is this
setting us back?

1376
00:51:57,251 --> 00:51:59,586
Why do you care?
We're doing better than ever.

1377
00:51:59,620 --> 00:52:00,454
Yeah, about that.

1378
00:52:00,487 --> 00:52:02,623
Jasmine's still
not returning calls.

1379
00:52:02,656 --> 00:52:03,890
Neither is Trish or Lucy.

1380
00:52:03,923 --> 00:52:05,058
Okay. I'll look into it.

1381
00:52:05,091 --> 00:52:06,593
Oh, and you still have to buy
raffle tickets from me.

1382
00:52:06,627 --> 00:52:07,193
- Don't forget.
- Right.

1383
00:52:07,227 --> 00:52:09,162
Yeah. I have the money.

1384
00:52:09,195 --> 00:52:11,130
Hey, Uncle Art, look at Wilbur.

1385
00:52:11,164 --> 00:52:12,865
Wow. Is that a tutu?

1386
00:52:12,899 --> 00:52:15,168
[laughing]

1387
00:52:15,201 --> 00:52:17,003
Okay, come here.
Let me see this.

1388
00:52:17,036 --> 00:52:18,639
You're crazy!

1389
00:52:18,672 --> 00:52:20,940
♪ You look fabulous!

1390
00:52:20,973 --> 00:52:21,642
Thanks, mami.

1391
00:52:21,675 --> 00:52:22,875
So do you.

1392
00:52:22,909 --> 00:52:25,245
Thank you.

1393
00:52:25,279 --> 00:52:26,413
Okay, I gotta talk to you.

1394
00:52:26,447 --> 00:52:26,946
Why can't we all just
have a good time?

1395
00:52:26,979 --> 00:52:29,182
Come on.

1396
00:52:29,216 --> 00:52:29,717
Look. If it's about Simone,
I don't want to hear it. Okay?

1397
00:52:29,750 --> 00:52:31,652
What's done is done.

1398
00:52:31,685 --> 00:52:33,354
It's about Mia.

1399
00:52:33,387 --> 00:52:34,221
What about her?

1400
00:52:34,254 --> 00:52:35,622
You're gonna
have to tell her, Anna.

1401
00:52:35,656 --> 00:52:37,624
Tell her what?

1402
00:52:37,658 --> 00:52:39,660
- About what you do.
- Why would I do that?

1403
00:52:39,693 --> 00:52:42,061
[Letty] Because
she's been asking questions

1404
00:52:42,095 --> 00:52:43,330
and I can't keep lying for you.

1405
00:52:43,364 --> 00:52:45,965
Look. She's 16.
She's not stupid.

1406
00:52:45,998 --> 00:52:47,301
It's better
if it comes from you,

1407
00:52:47,334 --> 00:52:48,535
because if she figures
it out on her...

1408
00:52:48,569 --> 00:52:49,202
I'll think about it, okay?

1409
00:52:49,236 --> 00:52:51,572
Do more than think about it.

1410
00:52:51,605 --> 00:52:53,440
You tell her, or I will.

1411
00:52:53,474 --> 00:52:54,608
Jesus, Letty. Cake!

1412
00:52:54,641 --> 00:52:55,642
Just sayin'.

1413
00:52:55,676 --> 00:52:56,909
[phone rings]

1414
00:52:56,943 --> 00:52:58,077
This is Anna.

1415
00:52:58,111 --> 00:52:59,680
[guests]
♪ Happy birthday to you

1416
00:52:59,713 --> 00:53:02,181
Lola, hey, I really can't...

1417
00:53:02,216 --> 00:53:05,017
♪ Happy birthday, dear Mia

1418
00:53:05,051 --> 00:53:07,221
♪ Happy birthday...

1419
00:53:07,254 --> 00:53:09,021
I'll be right there.
Give me 20 minutes.

1420
00:53:09,055 --> 00:53:10,357
♪ ...to you

1421
00:53:10,391 --> 00:53:12,191
[all cheering]

1422
00:53:12,226 --> 00:53:14,528
[Letty] Make a wish, baby.

1423
00:53:14,561 --> 00:53:15,662
[blowing]

1424
00:53:15,696 --> 00:53:17,297
[all cheering]

1425
00:53:18,998 --> 00:53:20,434
[cheering]

1426
00:53:22,101 --> 00:53:24,438
[Art] DJ, music again!

1427
00:53:29,976 --> 00:53:31,545
This better be good.

1428
00:53:31,578 --> 00:53:33,012
[sighing]

1429
00:53:35,449 --> 00:53:36,583
[Anna]
<i>Robert Sanford, age 55.</i>

1430
00:53:36,617 --> 00:53:40,186
<i>Ran an international
online gambling casino.</i>

1431
00:53:40,220 --> 00:53:43,055
<i>Net worth: 5.6 billion.</i>

1432
00:53:43,089 --> 00:53:45,325
<i>Alias: Mr. Cellophane.</i>

1433
00:53:45,359 --> 00:53:47,026
Tell Anna what you told me.

1434
00:53:47,059 --> 00:53:48,495
She left me tied to the chair

1435
00:53:48,529 --> 00:53:50,397
for two hours
while she went shopping

1436
00:53:50,431 --> 00:53:51,465
with my card.

1437
00:53:51,498 --> 00:53:52,666
So?

1438
00:53:52,699 --> 00:53:53,199
I got a bracelet for Mia

1439
00:53:53,233 --> 00:53:55,168
and a purse for you.

1440
00:53:55,201 --> 00:53:57,337
And I bought the Shakespeare
collection for myself.

1441
00:53:57,371 --> 00:53:59,606
<i>King Lear's</i>
always been my favorite.

1442
00:53:59,640 --> 00:54:01,040
And I got room service.

1443
00:54:01,073 --> 00:54:02,709
All the room service.

1444
00:54:02,743 --> 00:54:04,043
Strawberries?

1445
00:54:04,076 --> 00:54:05,712
I want my money back.

1446
00:54:05,746 --> 00:54:08,348
Were you bad, Bob?
Did you disobey Mistress?

1447
00:54:08,382 --> 00:54:09,716
He was nine minutes late.

1448
00:54:09,750 --> 00:54:13,287
Mistress was displeased.

1449
00:54:13,320 --> 00:54:13,854
He had to be punished.

1450
00:54:13,887 --> 00:54:15,589
I'm not paying for this!

1451
00:54:15,622 --> 00:54:17,089
You're absolutely right.

1452
00:54:20,059 --> 00:54:21,261
You're paying double.

1453
00:54:21,295 --> 00:54:22,094
You broke the rules,

1454
00:54:22,128 --> 00:54:24,231
you were disrespectful
to Mistress,

1455
00:54:24,264 --> 00:54:26,032
and you got me out of
my kid's Sweet 16 party.

1456
00:54:26,065 --> 00:54:30,737
You know how often a Sweet 16
happens in a kid's life, Bob?

1457
00:54:30,771 --> 00:54:32,138
Once.

1458
00:54:32,171 --> 00:54:35,007
Exactly. So double, plus tip.

1459
00:54:35,041 --> 00:54:36,210
And I don't care
if she leaves you

1460
00:54:36,243 --> 00:54:37,511
tied up like this
till morning.

1461
00:54:41,248 --> 00:54:42,616
Do we understand each other?

1462
00:54:42,649 --> 00:54:44,183
Mm-hmm.

1463
00:54:44,218 --> 00:54:44,918
Apologize to your mistress.

1464
00:54:44,952 --> 00:54:47,287
[muffled]
I'm sorry, Mistress.

1465
00:54:47,321 --> 00:54:48,020
And you're also buying
100 raffle tickets

1466
00:54:48,054 --> 00:54:49,756
to support the Eastside Eagles.

1467
00:54:49,790 --> 00:54:50,791
Are we clear?

1468
00:54:50,824 --> 00:54:52,593
Mm-hmm.

1469
00:54:52,626 --> 00:54:55,262
He's all yours, Lola.

1470
00:55:06,172 --> 00:55:07,274
[tires screeching]

1471
00:55:08,709 --> 00:55:09,676
Mom?

1472
00:55:11,110 --> 00:55:12,078
Why aren't you in bed?

1473
00:55:12,111 --> 00:55:13,145
Why are you sneaking around?

1474
00:55:13,179 --> 00:55:15,081
What's up with you lately?

1475
00:55:15,114 --> 00:55:16,817
You just had an amazing
Sweet 16 party.

1476
00:55:16,850 --> 00:55:19,151
You missed
the last half of it.

1477
00:55:19,185 --> 00:55:20,821
I had an emergency at work.

1478
00:55:20,854 --> 00:55:23,189
- With "head-hunting"?
- Yes.

1479
00:55:23,223 --> 00:55:24,658
What was it?

1480
00:55:25,759 --> 00:55:28,094
A client wasn't happy
and didn't want to pay.

1481
00:55:28,127 --> 00:55:29,830
That couldn't wait
until Monday?

1482
00:55:29,863 --> 00:55:31,331
That's the business.

1483
00:55:31,365 --> 00:55:32,332
What do you want me to do?

1484
00:55:32,366 --> 00:55:34,468
It just paid for your party
now, didn't it?

1485
00:55:34,501 --> 00:55:34,968
You wouldn't lie to me,
would you, Mom?

1486
00:55:35,002 --> 00:55:38,137
Mia, what is this?

1487
00:55:38,170 --> 00:55:39,706
Why can't you just say no?

1488
00:55:39,740 --> 00:55:42,609
No. I wouldn't lie to you.

1489
00:55:42,643 --> 00:55:44,176
Go to bed.

1490
00:55:48,180 --> 00:55:50,182
[sighing]

1491
00:55:52,252 --> 00:55:54,421
- Here you go.
- Hey.

1492
00:55:56,256 --> 00:55:58,859
[bill counter clacking]

1493
00:55:58,892 --> 00:56:01,762
Have you gotten
any dropped calls recently?

1494
00:56:01,795 --> 00:56:02,663
-A few. Why?

1495
00:56:02,696 --> 00:56:04,431
- So have I.
- Me too.

1496
00:56:05,265 --> 00:56:06,366
It's not good, Anna.

1497
00:56:06,400 --> 00:56:07,367
[Art] And it's not just that.

1498
00:56:07,401 --> 00:56:09,201
It's the girls, too...
Jasmine, Trish, Lucy.

1499
00:56:09,236 --> 00:56:11,137
Word on the street

1500
00:56:11,170 --> 00:56:12,606
is they're getting poached.

1501
00:56:12,639 --> 00:56:13,574
By who?

1502
00:56:13,607 --> 00:56:14,875
Don't know.
Someone who's new to the game.

1503
00:56:14,908 --> 00:56:16,510
And they're not only
taking the girls,

1504
00:56:16,543 --> 00:56:17,344
they're taking the clients,

1505
00:56:17,377 --> 00:56:19,580
and they're marking
their territory.

1506
00:56:19,613 --> 00:56:20,581
I think it's...

1507
00:56:21,180 --> 00:56:23,450
What?

1508
00:56:23,483 --> 00:56:24,484
Time.

1509
00:56:24,518 --> 00:56:26,118
Might be time to get out, Anna.

1510
00:56:26,152 --> 00:56:27,254
No!

1511
00:56:27,287 --> 00:56:29,256
No! Why are you even
talking like that?

1512
00:56:29,289 --> 00:56:30,691
How many times
do I have to say it?

1513
00:56:30,724 --> 00:56:32,893
No amount of money
is worth your freedom,

1514
00:56:32,926 --> 00:56:34,126
and listen to your gut.

1515
00:56:34,160 --> 00:56:35,062
When things get weird,

1516
00:56:35,094 --> 00:56:37,196
it's the universe telling you
it's time.

1517
00:56:40,767 --> 00:56:41,568
No.

1518
00:56:41,602 --> 00:56:43,904
No, I'm not
gonna be intimidated.

1519
00:56:43,937 --> 00:56:45,272
What kind of message
does that send?

1520
00:56:45,305 --> 00:56:46,306
That you're smart.

1521
00:56:46,340 --> 00:56:47,474
That I'm scared!

1522
00:56:47,507 --> 00:56:48,909
If I have to dangle someone else
out the window, I will.

1523
00:56:48,942 --> 00:56:51,678
- Anna.
- We are business as usual.

1524
00:56:51,712 --> 00:56:54,180
Letty, go into the city
and start asking around.

1525
00:56:54,214 --> 00:56:54,915
See what you can find out
about whoever's messing

1526
00:56:54,948 --> 00:56:57,451
with my bottom line.

1527
00:56:57,484 --> 00:56:59,286
Arthur, if you're spooked,
we can reroute websites,

1528
00:56:59,319 --> 00:57:00,887
start another LLC,
and pause deposits.

1529
00:57:00,921 --> 00:57:03,523
Happy?

1530
00:57:04,758 --> 00:57:05,759
Okay.

1531
00:57:14,935 --> 00:57:16,269
[Anna] <i>I was losing her.</i>

1532
00:57:16,303 --> 00:57:17,604
<i>I could feel it.</i>

1533
00:57:17,638 --> 00:57:19,306
<i>Kids know
when you're lying to them,</i>

1534
00:57:19,339 --> 00:57:22,676
<i>and if they can't trust you,
they resent you.</i>

1535
00:57:23,777 --> 00:57:25,278
Put that away.

1536
00:57:25,312 --> 00:57:27,714
I want to talk to you
about something.

1537
00:57:27,748 --> 00:57:29,616
You know that,
ever since Dad died,

1538
00:57:29,650 --> 00:57:31,318
I work very hard

1539
00:57:31,351 --> 00:57:33,152
to provide for you
and your brother, right?

1540
00:57:33,387 --> 00:57:35,789
And I love you both
so much.

1541
00:57:35,822 --> 00:57:39,826
How would you feel
if I told you that I...

1542
00:57:41,228 --> 00:57:44,231
That you...?

1543
00:57:44,264 --> 00:57:47,868
[sighs]

1544
00:57:47,901 --> 00:57:49,569
...Have a boyfriend.

1545
00:57:49,603 --> 00:57:50,704
That's it?

1546
00:57:51,872 --> 00:57:53,340
That's it.

1547
00:57:53,373 --> 00:57:55,242
Are you sure
there's nothing else?

1548
00:57:55,275 --> 00:57:57,444
That's it, kiddo.

1549
00:57:57,477 --> 00:57:59,846
I'd be happy for you, Mom.

1550
00:58:02,015 --> 00:58:04,951
[♪♪]

1551
00:58:05,886 --> 00:58:07,954
[phone rings]

1552
00:58:07,988 --> 00:58:10,323
This is Anna.

1553
00:58:10,357 --> 00:58:12,325
[line hangs up]

1554
00:58:12,359 --> 00:58:14,461
[dial tone buzzing]

1555
00:58:16,363 --> 00:58:18,932
[Anna sighs]

1556
00:58:18,965 --> 00:58:21,468
[phone rings]

1557
00:58:21,501 --> 00:58:22,201
[snaps] Who is this?

1558
00:58:22,235 --> 00:58:24,237
Anna. It's me.
Are you okay?

1559
00:58:24,271 --> 00:58:26,640
Yeah. Yeah,
I just got a little spooked.

1560
00:58:26,673 --> 00:58:28,909
I have good news and bad news.

1561
00:58:28,942 --> 00:58:31,912
The good news is, I found out
who's poaching your girls.

1562
00:58:31,945 --> 00:58:32,446
Who is it?

1563
00:58:32,479 --> 00:58:34,948
That's the bad news.

1564
00:58:34,981 --> 00:58:36,483
It's Vicky.

1565
00:58:38,051 --> 00:58:41,288
[Anna] <i>That's when
I realized Letty was right.</i>

1566
00:58:41,321 --> 00:58:43,356
<i>I'd made a mistake.</i>

1567
00:58:43,390 --> 00:58:44,391
<i>Gone too far.</i>

1568
00:58:44,424 --> 00:58:46,760
<i>I had to be smarter.</i>

1569
00:58:49,730 --> 00:58:50,697
Anna?

1570
00:58:50,731 --> 00:58:52,933
You did good.

1571
00:58:52,966 --> 00:58:53,967
I'll take care of it.

1572
00:58:54,000 --> 00:58:54,801
<i>I don't want</i>

1573
00:58:54,835 --> 00:58:56,636
any part
of your "taking care" of it.

1574
00:58:56,670 --> 00:58:59,940
Anna, now might be
a really good time

1575
00:58:59,973 --> 00:59:00,941
to consider getting...

1576
00:59:00,974 --> 00:59:02,309
<i>We'll talk tomorrow.</i>

1577
00:59:02,342 --> 00:59:04,911
[car tires screeching]

1578
00:59:07,080 --> 00:59:09,916
[engine rumbles]

1579
00:59:13,954 --> 00:59:15,021
Who are you?

1580
00:59:15,055 --> 00:59:16,923
Who sent you?

1581
00:59:16,957 --> 00:59:18,658
You think you can scare me?

1582
00:59:18,692 --> 00:59:19,426
You think you can
show up at my house?

1583
00:59:19,459 --> 00:59:21,027
Mom?

1584
00:59:21,061 --> 00:59:22,963
What the hell?

1585
00:59:22,996 --> 00:59:24,798
[groans and sighs]

1586
00:59:25,899 --> 00:59:27,601
Are you drunk?

1587
00:59:27,634 --> 00:59:28,702
No.

1588
00:59:29,903 --> 00:59:32,272
Get outta here before I call
the cops, you little creep.

1589
00:59:34,341 --> 00:59:36,943
Inside. Now.

1590
00:59:39,913 --> 00:59:42,015
Since when do you drink?

1591
00:59:42,048 --> 00:59:43,784
I had a wine cooler.

1592
00:59:43,817 --> 00:59:44,351
Big deal.

1593
00:59:44,384 --> 00:59:46,353
And who was that guy?

1594
00:59:46,386 --> 00:59:48,088
A boy who's my friend.

1595
00:59:48,121 --> 00:59:49,623
So now you have
a secret boyfriend?

1596
00:59:49,656 --> 00:59:51,324
It's better than
a secret life.

1597
00:59:51,358 --> 00:59:52,492
What's that supposed to mean?

1598
00:59:52,526 --> 00:59:54,427
You think I'm stupid?

1599
00:59:54,461 --> 00:59:57,631
You don't just run a salon.

1600
00:59:57,664 --> 00:59:59,099
Marty's dad's a head-hunter,

1601
00:59:59,132 --> 01:00:00,500
and he has an office

1602
01:00:00,534 --> 01:00:02,736
and normal business hours

1603
01:00:02,769 --> 01:00:05,572
and doesn't always
pay for things in hundreds.

1604
01:00:06,706 --> 01:00:08,975
I know
what you do for a living.

1605
01:00:10,877 --> 01:00:12,712
What is it
that you think I do?

1606
01:00:12,746 --> 01:00:13,446
Ask away.

1607
01:00:13,480 --> 01:00:15,749
20 questions. Go.

1608
01:00:15,782 --> 01:00:17,384
- Are you a millionaire?
- Yes.

1609
01:00:17,417 --> 01:00:18,785
Are you paid in cash?

1610
01:00:18,819 --> 01:00:19,352
Yes.

1611
01:00:19,386 --> 01:00:21,454
Is what you do legal?

1612
01:00:22,856 --> 01:00:23,824
No.

1613
01:00:23,857 --> 01:00:25,892
If someone found out,
could you go to jail?

1614
01:00:25,926 --> 01:00:27,861
Don't lie.

1615
01:00:29,529 --> 01:00:31,731
Yes.

1616
01:00:33,066 --> 01:00:33,333
Are you a drug dealer?

1617
01:00:33,366 --> 01:00:35,101
What?

1618
01:00:35,135 --> 01:00:37,804
Listen to me, Mia.
I am not a drug dealer.

1619
01:00:37,838 --> 01:00:40,040
Okay?
I would never do that.

1620
01:00:40,073 --> 01:00:40,974
Then what?

1621
01:00:46,413 --> 01:00:48,481
I'm a madam.

1622
01:00:49,182 --> 01:00:51,885
[♪♪]

1623
01:00:52,519 --> 01:00:54,855
[sobs]

1624
01:00:57,490 --> 01:00:58,992
[sighs heavily]

1625
01:01:03,930 --> 01:01:05,165
Okay, so...

1626
01:01:05,198 --> 01:01:06,499
[Anna]
<i>After she'd calmed down,</i>

1627
01:01:06,533 --> 01:01:08,835
<i>I started at the beginning
and told her everything...</i>

1628
01:01:08,869 --> 01:01:09,502
<i>from "Enema Man"</i>

1629
01:01:09,536 --> 01:01:11,638
<i>to "Russian James Bond".</i>

1630
01:01:12,572 --> 01:01:13,440
<i>I didn't want to lose her.</i>

1631
01:01:13,473 --> 01:01:16,076
<i>She deserved the truth.</i>

1632
01:01:16,109 --> 01:01:17,245
<i>Coming clean to her</i>

1633
01:01:17,278 --> 01:01:20,480
<i>was the second biggest gamble
of my life.</i>

1634
01:01:20,513 --> 01:01:21,481
Take the money.

1635
01:01:21,514 --> 01:01:23,650
So what do you think?

1636
01:01:24,184 --> 01:01:27,053
Honestly?

1637
01:01:28,555 --> 01:01:30,824
I kinda think it's cool.

1638
01:01:30,857 --> 01:01:32,859
[Mia laughs]

1639
01:01:32,893 --> 01:01:33,393
Oh!

1640
01:01:37,597 --> 01:01:40,200
But if it's illegal
and you get caught,

1641
01:01:40,234 --> 01:01:42,202
what happens to us?

1642
01:01:42,236 --> 01:01:44,137
I won't get caught.

1643
01:01:44,170 --> 01:01:45,906
No one ever thinks
they're gonna get caught

1644
01:01:45,939 --> 01:01:46,606
and then they do.

1645
01:01:46,640 --> 01:01:48,708
What would we do without you?

1646
01:01:48,742 --> 01:01:49,976
It's not gonna happen.

1647
01:01:50,010 --> 01:01:50,877
How do you know?

1648
01:01:50,911 --> 01:01:53,513
Is there something else
you could do?

1649
01:01:55,216 --> 01:01:56,883
[sighs]

1650
01:01:58,585 --> 01:01:59,253
Okay, let's make a deal.

1651
01:01:59,287 --> 01:02:02,756
I will look into a new career,

1652
01:02:02,789 --> 01:02:06,059
if you get back on the horse...
literally.

1653
01:02:07,160 --> 01:02:08,128
Deal?

1654
01:02:08,161 --> 01:02:09,162
Deal.

1655
01:02:09,195 --> 01:02:10,231
[Anna] <i>But first,</i>

1656
01:02:10,264 --> 01:02:11,898
<i>I had to take care of a problem
I'd created</i>

1657
01:02:11,932 --> 01:02:13,700
<i>that was biting me
in the ass.</i>

1658
01:02:13,733 --> 01:02:15,702
<i>[door buzzer ringing]</i>

1659
01:02:19,005 --> 01:02:21,174
<i>I found out
where Vicky was living</i>

1660
01:02:21,208 --> 01:02:22,542
<i>and placed an ad
with her address</i>

1661
01:02:22,575 --> 01:02:24,511
in the back of a men's magazine.

1662
01:02:24,544 --> 01:02:26,079
Regular guys
just started showing up,

1663
01:02:26,112 --> 01:02:28,581
looking for a $50 quickie.

1664
01:02:28,615 --> 01:02:29,816
[pounding on door]

1665
01:02:29,849 --> 01:02:33,586
<i>But Vicky thought it was the mob
and assumed I sent them.</i>

1666
01:02:35,622 --> 01:02:37,524
[thumping on door]

1667
01:02:37,557 --> 01:02:39,125
<i>That's all it took for her</i>

1668
01:02:39,159 --> 01:02:41,995
<i>to pack up, quit the business,
and go underground.</i>

1669
01:02:42,028 --> 01:02:44,531
<i>My poached girls came back
and I was back on track.</i>

1670
01:02:47,067 --> 01:02:49,803
<i>But my promise to Mia
wasn't going as well.</i>

1671
01:02:49,836 --> 01:02:50,804
<i>As far as transitions go,</i>

1672
01:02:50,837 --> 01:02:52,273
<i>I didn't even know
where to start.</i>

1673
01:02:52,306 --> 01:02:53,473
<i>I had no ideas.</i>

1674
01:02:56,176 --> 01:02:57,877
<i>And then I just got lucky.</i>

1675
01:02:57,911 --> 01:02:59,280
<i>There it was.
Right in front of me.</i>

1676
01:02:59,313 --> 01:03:00,513
Mom. We're gonna be late.

1677
01:03:00,547 --> 01:03:02,582
Just a second, kiddo.

1678
01:03:07,554 --> 01:03:09,823
<i>Commercial real estate.</i>

1679
01:03:09,856 --> 01:03:10,957
<i>A chance to go legit.</i>

1680
01:03:10,991 --> 01:03:12,058
<i>I kept thinking</i>

1681
01:03:12,092 --> 01:03:14,627
<i>about Owen
and his building and legacy.</i>

1682
01:03:14,661 --> 01:03:17,630
<i>I wanted to create
something I could leave behind,</i>

1683
01:03:17,664 --> 01:03:20,066
<i>something that my kids
and grandkids</i>

1684
01:03:20,100 --> 01:03:20,500
<i>could be proud of.</i>

1685
01:03:20,533 --> 01:03:22,635
[phone rings]

1686
01:03:22,669 --> 01:03:24,537
Hey, Cass.

1687
01:03:24,571 --> 01:03:25,605
No. Don't be nervous.

1688
01:03:25,638 --> 01:03:26,307
You're gonna do great.

1689
01:03:26,340 --> 01:03:28,309
Call me after, okay?

1690
01:03:28,342 --> 01:03:30,311
<i>That same day,</i>

1691
01:03:30,344 --> 01:03:31,445
<i>Cassidy was on her way</i>

1692
01:03:31,479 --> 01:03:32,213
<i>to spend an afternoon
with a new client</i>

1693
01:03:32,246 --> 01:03:35,282
<i>who came highly recommended.</i>

1694
01:03:36,783 --> 01:03:38,319
<i>Chester Corey, age 60.</i>

1695
01:03:38,352 --> 01:03:40,653
<i>Owner of
a mass media conglomerate</i>

1696
01:03:40,687 --> 01:03:42,323
<i>that you've definitely heard of,</i>

1697
01:03:42,356 --> 01:03:44,657
<i>and world renowned
collector of antiques.</i>

1698
01:03:44,691 --> 01:03:46,327
<i>Net worth: six billion.</i>

1699
01:03:46,360 --> 01:03:48,661
<i>Alias: Versailles.</i>

1700
01:03:48,695 --> 01:03:51,598
Raffle tickets!
Raffle tickets!

1701
01:03:51,631 --> 01:03:52,999
Support the Eastside Eagles!

1702
01:03:53,033 --> 01:03:54,335
Hi, you guys.
How many do you guys want?

1703
01:03:54,368 --> 01:03:56,770
Oh, wonderful! Okay. Great.

1704
01:03:56,803 --> 01:03:58,638
Thank you so much for supporting
the Eastside Eagles.

1705
01:03:58,671 --> 01:04:00,807
Raffle tickets, guys!

1706
01:04:00,840 --> 01:04:02,709
Hey! Hey-hey. How many?

1707
01:04:02,742 --> 01:04:05,945
[♪♪]

1708
01:04:09,716 --> 01:04:11,684
[thud]

1709
01:04:11,718 --> 01:04:13,653
[smack]

1710
01:04:14,388 --> 01:04:15,688
[dark theme plays]

1711
01:04:15,722 --> 01:04:16,956
Let me go!

1712
01:04:18,892 --> 01:04:21,262
[Cassidy cries out
as blows land]

1713
01:04:21,295 --> 01:04:23,596
Let me go!

1714
01:04:23,630 --> 01:04:24,697
Look at that "D"! Defense!

1715
01:04:24,731 --> 01:04:26,666
Whoo-whoo!

1716
01:04:26,699 --> 01:04:28,735
Let's go, guys!
Come on! Teamwork!

1717
01:04:28,768 --> 01:04:30,170
Come on! You got this!

1718
01:04:32,639 --> 01:04:33,706
You're quiet.
You all right?

1719
01:04:33,740 --> 01:04:36,042
No, yeah, I'm fine.
I'm just... Everything's good.

1720
01:04:36,076 --> 01:04:37,577
Come on, John Christopher!
Let's go, baby!

1721
01:04:39,913 --> 01:04:41,848
- Let's go.
- Come on!

1722
01:04:41,881 --> 01:04:42,582
Let's go, let's go!

1723
01:04:42,615 --> 01:04:44,251
[Art] Come on, guys.
Let's go.

1724
01:04:44,285 --> 01:04:47,087
Go. Go, go, go. Go... whoo!

1725
01:04:47,120 --> 01:04:47,488
Oh, yeah! Yes!

1726
01:04:47,521 --> 01:04:49,356
[shrieking]

1727
01:04:49,390 --> 01:04:52,659
[all cheering]

1728
01:04:52,692 --> 01:04:52,959
Whoo-hoo!

1729
01:04:52,992 --> 01:04:55,195
Yeah!

1730
01:04:55,229 --> 01:04:56,696
Whoo!

1731
01:04:56,729 --> 01:04:57,931
[phone rings]

1732
01:04:59,400 --> 01:05:01,701
Hey, Cass. How'd it go?

1733
01:05:04,305 --> 01:05:05,839
Cassidy, are you okay?

1734
01:05:06,407 --> 01:05:08,409
[♪♪]

1735
01:05:08,442 --> 01:05:10,877
That son of a bitch.

1736
01:05:10,910 --> 01:05:12,879
Keep it down, Anna.

1737
01:05:12,912 --> 01:05:15,382
I'm sorry!
It's just that son of a bitch!

1738
01:05:15,416 --> 01:05:18,751
He didn't seem
like the type to...

1739
01:05:18,785 --> 01:05:20,720
I can't go back to my place.

1740
01:05:20,753 --> 01:05:22,856
You can stay here

1741
01:05:22,889 --> 01:05:26,025
for as long as you need, okay?

1742
01:05:31,798 --> 01:05:35,101
You know we can't go
to the cops, right?

1743
01:05:38,004 --> 01:05:38,472
I-I know.

1744
01:05:38,506 --> 01:05:40,840
But I promise you,

1745
01:05:40,874 --> 01:05:43,244
he is being dealt with
as we speak

1746
01:05:43,277 --> 01:05:47,214
and this will never
happen again, okay?

1747
01:05:47,248 --> 01:05:49,082
[sobs]

1748
01:05:49,115 --> 01:05:49,649
[Anna sighs]

1749
01:05:56,357 --> 01:05:57,258
I'm sorry.

1750
01:05:58,359 --> 01:06:00,126
Go ahead.
Let me have it.

1751
01:06:00,160 --> 01:06:01,127
I deserve it.

1752
01:06:01,161 --> 01:06:01,794
This is on you.

1753
01:06:01,828 --> 01:06:03,930
You don't think I know that?

1754
01:06:03,963 --> 01:06:04,664
I'm going to make it right.

1755
01:06:04,697 --> 01:06:07,434
Well, you can do it without me.

1756
01:06:07,468 --> 01:06:09,403
What's that supposed to mean?

1757
01:06:09,436 --> 01:06:11,070
15 years in the business,

1758
01:06:11,104 --> 01:06:13,706
and I never had a man
put a hand on one of my girls!

1759
01:06:13,740 --> 01:06:15,476
You almost had
one shoot up the place,

1760
01:06:15,509 --> 01:06:17,010
or did you forget that?

1761
01:06:17,043 --> 01:06:17,911
I quit.

1762
01:06:17,944 --> 01:06:19,946
You can't quit,

1763
01:06:19,979 --> 01:06:21,948
because I already fired you!

1764
01:06:23,517 --> 01:06:25,252
[door slams]

1765
01:06:25,286 --> 01:06:26,320
[shattering]

1766
01:06:26,353 --> 01:06:27,388
["Versailles" cries out]

1767
01:06:27,421 --> 01:06:29,055
What's wrong with you?

1768
01:06:29,088 --> 01:06:30,924
[groans]

1769
01:06:33,394 --> 01:06:35,028
[♪♪]

1770
01:06:35,061 --> 01:06:37,331
No. That's priceless.
You can't do that!

1771
01:06:40,534 --> 01:06:43,337
[grunting]

1772
01:06:54,814 --> 01:06:55,848
So, what do you think?

1773
01:06:55,882 --> 01:06:57,518
Can we afford it?

1774
01:06:57,551 --> 01:06:59,786
It's a stretch,

1775
01:06:59,819 --> 01:07:01,988
but I think
I can make the numbers work.

1776
01:07:02,021 --> 01:07:03,890
But this is good.
Really good.

1777
01:07:03,923 --> 01:07:05,359
Whatever happened to the girl

1778
01:07:05,392 --> 01:07:08,061
scrubbing the floors
after Enema Man paid us a visit?

1779
01:07:08,094 --> 01:07:08,995
[laughs]

1780
01:07:09,028 --> 01:07:10,997
She's going legit.

1781
01:07:11,864 --> 01:07:13,267
I'm proud of you.

1782
01:07:14,535 --> 01:07:15,068
Thanks.

1783
01:07:15,101 --> 01:07:17,338
You're gonna buy this?

1784
01:07:17,371 --> 01:07:19,506
Sure. Why not?

1785
01:07:19,540 --> 01:07:21,007
Consider it an investment.

1786
01:07:21,040 --> 01:07:22,809
And after you graduate
from college,

1787
01:07:22,842 --> 01:07:23,910
you can come help me.

1788
01:07:23,943 --> 01:07:25,945
This will all be yours
and your brother's one day.

1789
01:07:25,979 --> 01:07:27,448
Your legacy.

1790
01:07:27,481 --> 01:07:29,015
Let's do it.

1791
01:07:29,048 --> 01:07:30,016
<i>[Anna] So there I was,</i>

1792
01:07:30,049 --> 01:07:31,017
<i>on my way to becoming</i>

1793
01:07:31,050 --> 01:07:33,152
<i>a commercial real estate
developer,</i>

1794
01:07:33,186 --> 01:07:34,954
<i>and I had to admit,
coming clean and going legit,</i>

1795
01:07:34,988 --> 01:07:37,123
<i>it felt good...</i>

1796
01:07:37,156 --> 01:07:39,892
<i>but there was still
one person I was lying to.</i>

1797
01:07:39,926 --> 01:07:42,429
- Home?
- Work.

1798
01:07:43,597 --> 01:07:44,897
Salon's open late.

1799
01:07:44,931 --> 01:07:47,468
Other work.

1800
01:07:47,501 --> 01:07:49,536
Right. Head-hunting.

1801
01:07:49,570 --> 01:07:51,971
You get calls this late?

1802
01:07:52,005 --> 01:07:54,375
Sometimes, yeah.

1803
01:07:54,408 --> 01:07:54,907
Is that a good thing?

1804
01:07:54,941 --> 01:07:56,909
I mean, is it, uh...

1805
01:07:56,943 --> 01:08:00,381
[Anna] <i>I was on a roll
with this whole honesty thing,</i>

1806
01:08:00,414 --> 01:08:02,849
<i>and after all, I mean,
how bad could his reaction be?</i>

1807
01:08:02,882 --> 01:08:04,117
<i>But I still couldn't tell him.</i>

1808
01:08:04,150 --> 01:08:07,521
<i>That was a gamble
I just wasn't willing to take.</i>

1809
01:08:07,554 --> 01:08:10,457
<i>We still had a shot
at our happily-ever-after.</i>

1810
01:08:14,328 --> 01:08:18,299
[♪♪]

1811
01:08:21,034 --> 01:08:23,337
[♪♪]

1812
01:08:23,370 --> 01:08:24,837
<i>I was all in...</i>

1813
01:08:24,871 --> 01:08:27,940
<i>the third-biggest gamble
of my life.</i>

1814
01:08:27,974 --> 01:08:30,277
<i>$30,000 a month mortgage,</i>

1815
01:08:30,311 --> 01:08:33,347
<i>$30,000 a year
in property tax alone.</i>

1816
01:08:34,947 --> 01:08:37,817
<i>But I wasn't
out of my business just yet.</i>

1817
01:08:45,259 --> 01:08:46,926
<i>I couldn't just walk away
from the business I'd built.</i>

1818
01:08:46,959 --> 01:08:47,960
<i>My girls depended on me.</i>

1819
01:08:47,994 --> 01:08:48,995
<i>They needed me.</i>

1820
01:08:49,028 --> 01:08:50,897
<i>It was imperative</i>

1821
01:08:50,930 --> 01:08:52,366
<i>that I leave them
in good hands,</i>

1822
01:08:52,399 --> 01:08:54,368
<i>and there was only
one woman for the job.</i>

1823
01:08:58,004 --> 01:09:00,341
Wow.

1824
01:09:00,374 --> 01:09:01,974
It's a lot...
it's a lot of responsibility,

1825
01:09:02,008 --> 01:09:04,010
but I wouldn't be asking you

1826
01:09:04,043 --> 01:09:05,512
if I didn't think
you could do it,

1827
01:09:05,546 --> 01:09:07,947
and if I didn't think it'd be
beneficial to the both of us.

1828
01:09:07,980 --> 01:09:10,116
You're really getting out?

1829
01:09:11,418 --> 01:09:13,520
For the kids.

1830
01:09:13,554 --> 01:09:15,154
Mia especially.

1831
01:09:15,188 --> 01:09:17,090
Do you remember
what you told me once?

1832
01:09:17,123 --> 01:09:18,991
"They get what they want
whenever they want,

1833
01:09:19,025 --> 01:09:21,060
but there's one thing
they always want

1834
01:09:21,094 --> 01:09:22,028
that we don't
have to give them.

1835
01:09:22,061 --> 01:09:24,097
We can make them pay for it."

1836
01:09:24,130 --> 01:09:25,998
Even then,
they can just take it...

1837
01:09:26,032 --> 01:09:27,267
you left that part out.

1838
01:09:27,301 --> 01:09:28,369
I know.

1839
01:09:28,402 --> 01:09:31,003
I'm not saying yes,
but I'm not saying no, either.

1840
01:09:31,037 --> 01:09:34,641
I just...
I need to think about it.

1841
01:09:34,675 --> 01:09:36,410
Take all the time.

1842
01:09:37,511 --> 01:09:37,877
Okay.

1843
01:09:40,280 --> 01:09:41,348
Whoo-hoo!

1844
01:09:41,382 --> 01:09:44,585
Whoo! Yeah, Mia!

1845
01:09:45,017 --> 01:09:47,388
Yes! Yes, Mia!

1846
01:09:50,957 --> 01:09:52,158
- [horse huffs]
- Whoa.

1847
01:09:52,191 --> 01:09:54,528
You did it.
How does it feel?

1848
01:09:54,561 --> 01:09:56,397
Good.

1849
01:09:56,430 --> 01:09:59,333
Why don't you go again,
just to make sure?

1850
01:09:59,366 --> 01:10:00,634
Okay, Mom.

1851
01:10:00,667 --> 01:10:01,235
How's your stuff?

1852
01:10:01,268 --> 01:10:03,570
Are you officially out?

1853
01:10:03,604 --> 01:10:04,338
I'm working on it.

1854
01:10:04,371 --> 01:10:05,706
I'm gonna worry
until you are.

1855
01:10:05,739 --> 01:10:07,574
I know.

1856
01:10:07,608 --> 01:10:08,675
Go!

1857
01:10:08,709 --> 01:10:10,711
Tch-tch.

1858
01:10:10,744 --> 01:10:12,178
Good boy.

1859
01:10:13,045 --> 01:10:14,113
[Anna] <i>Two weeks had passed</i>

1860
01:10:14,147 --> 01:10:14,848
<i>and I still hadn't
heard from Cassidy.</i>

1861
01:10:14,882 --> 01:10:17,217
<i>I'd almost given up on her</i>

1862
01:10:17,251 --> 01:10:17,984
<i>and was looking to ask
another girl when...</i>

1863
01:10:18,017 --> 01:10:20,920
[phone rings]

1864
01:10:21,755 --> 01:10:24,123
Hey, Cass.

1865
01:10:24,157 --> 01:10:25,024
How are you?

1866
01:10:25,057 --> 01:10:27,059
<i>She was in,</i>

1867
01:10:27,093 --> 01:10:30,196
<i>which meant I was out.</i>

1868
01:10:31,265 --> 01:10:32,733
<i>Word got out
about my purchase</i>

1869
01:10:32,766 --> 01:10:34,000
<i>and, suddenly, I was more than</i>

1870
01:10:34,033 --> 01:10:36,002
<i>just the owner of a nail salon
and a soccer mom.</i>

1871
01:10:36,035 --> 01:10:37,003
<i>I was legit.</i>

1872
01:10:37,036 --> 01:10:39,606
<i>Respected.</i>

1873
01:10:39,640 --> 01:10:40,741
<i>Someone to look up to.</i>

1874
01:10:40,774 --> 01:10:43,377
And our award
for most valuable player

1875
01:10:43,410 --> 01:10:46,380
goes to...
John Christopher.

1876
01:10:46,413 --> 01:10:47,980
[cheering]

1877
01:10:48,014 --> 01:10:50,584
Great job!

1878
01:10:50,617 --> 01:10:52,352
Whoo-hoo!

1879
01:10:54,421 --> 01:10:58,325
As always, we want
to recognize the Eagle parent

1880
01:10:58,358 --> 01:11:00,661
who sold the most raffle tickets
this season.

1881
01:11:00,694 --> 01:11:02,529
Anna, come on up here.

1882
01:11:02,563 --> 01:11:03,730
[cheering]

1883
01:11:03,764 --> 01:11:06,032
Come get your trophy.

1884
01:11:06,065 --> 01:11:08,235
[applauding]

1885
01:11:15,542 --> 01:11:17,277
Hey, kiddo.

1886
01:11:17,311 --> 01:11:19,746
Why are you so happy?

1887
01:11:19,780 --> 01:11:21,047
I'm out.

1888
01:11:21,080 --> 01:11:22,316
Officially?

1889
01:11:22,349 --> 01:11:24,218
I just made my last call
a few minutes ago.

1890
01:11:24,251 --> 01:11:25,652
Cassidy's taking over,

1891
01:11:25,686 --> 01:11:27,721
and if she needs help,
Arthur's standing by.

1892
01:11:27,754 --> 01:11:29,021
Congratulations, Mom.

1893
01:11:29,055 --> 01:11:31,123
I'm so proud of you.

1894
01:11:31,825 --> 01:11:34,328
[♪♪]

1895
01:11:34,361 --> 01:11:36,763
So... everything's okay?

1896
01:11:36,797 --> 01:11:39,266
Better than okay.

1897
01:11:44,271 --> 01:11:46,640
<i>[television program plays]</i>

1898
01:12:01,855 --> 01:12:04,224
Anna, can we talk?

1899
01:12:04,258 --> 01:12:05,792
No, Arthur.
No business.

1900
01:12:05,826 --> 01:12:06,960
Okay? If Cass has a problem,
she needs to handle it herself.

1901
01:12:06,994 --> 01:12:10,330
That's how I learned,
that's how she's gonna learn.

1902
01:12:10,364 --> 01:12:12,299
- Right, but...
- No buts.

1903
01:12:12,332 --> 01:12:13,734
Real estate stuff only, Arthur.

1904
01:12:13,767 --> 01:12:14,668
I mean it.

1905
01:12:14,701 --> 01:12:15,936
- [reporter] <i>Breaking news...</i>
- Okay.

1906
01:12:15,969 --> 01:12:17,203
[reporter] <i>Financial systems
worldwide in a panic...</i>

1907
01:12:17,237 --> 01:12:18,839
Mom! Come quick.

1908
01:12:18,872 --> 01:12:21,441
<i>...moments after opening.</i>

1909
01:12:21,475 --> 01:12:22,209
<i>The Dow Jones has fallen
over 700 points...</i>

1910
01:12:22,242 --> 01:12:24,311
What's up?

1911
01:12:24,344 --> 01:12:24,978
<i>...the largest drop in history,
and more losses...</i>

1912
01:12:25,012 --> 01:12:27,347
[Anna] <i>The crash of 2008.</i>

1913
01:12:27,381 --> 01:12:30,751
<i>All my money, all of it,
was tied up in my real estate.</i>

1914
01:12:30,784 --> 01:12:33,587
<i>Now all of my assets
were underwater.</i>

1915
01:12:33,620 --> 01:12:37,123
<i>Just when I thought I was out,
I was pulled back in,</i>

1916
01:12:37,156 --> 01:12:39,058
<i>but I couldn't tell Mia.</i>

1917
01:12:43,564 --> 01:12:46,466
[♪♪]

1918
01:12:49,369 --> 01:12:50,504
[Anna] <i>If the market
hadn't crashed in 2008,</i>

1919
01:12:50,537 --> 01:12:52,873
<i>I would have been
a wealthy, legal land developer.</i>

1920
01:12:52,906 --> 01:12:55,842
<i>Not only was I on the hook
for a massive mortgage,</i>

1921
01:12:55,876 --> 01:12:56,944
<i>no one was buying
or building,</i>

1922
01:12:56,977 --> 01:12:58,879
<i>which meant I had
no source of income,</i>

1923
01:12:58,912 --> 01:13:00,747
<i>so I had to go back
to what I knew.</i>

1924
01:13:00,781 --> 01:13:01,815
Hi.

1925
01:13:01,848 --> 01:13:02,783
My name's Melody.

1926
01:13:02,816 --> 01:13:04,751
You know, like,
the best part of the song?

1927
01:13:04,785 --> 01:13:05,385
- Right.
- The melody.

1928
01:13:05,419 --> 01:13:08,522
[♪♪]

1929
01:13:08,555 --> 01:13:11,157
<i>But even though
my instincts warned against it,</i>

1930
01:13:11,190 --> 01:13:13,460
<i>I was willing
to give her a chance.</i>

1931
01:13:13,493 --> 01:13:15,796
Am I?

1932
01:13:15,829 --> 01:13:17,364
Do you want to have fun?

1933
01:13:18,265 --> 01:13:20,132
[Anna]
<i>Samuel Crawford. Age 43.</i>

1934
01:13:20,166 --> 01:13:22,836
<i>Made his money as a home good
buyer and distributor</i>

1935
01:13:22,869 --> 01:13:24,438
<i>to retail stores.</i>

1936
01:13:24,471 --> 01:13:26,373
<i>Net worth: six million.</i>

1937
01:13:26,406 --> 01:13:28,308
<i>Alias: Bargain Basement.</i>

1938
01:13:28,342 --> 01:13:30,176
All right. Let's do this.

1939
01:13:30,210 --> 01:13:31,478
Damn, girl!

1940
01:13:31,511 --> 01:13:32,479
Ho, ho!

1941
01:13:32,512 --> 01:13:33,080
[laughs]

1942
01:13:33,112 --> 01:13:35,649
Whoa, whoa. Easy, easy.

1943
01:13:35,682 --> 01:13:36,249
You okay?

1944
01:13:36,283 --> 01:13:37,217
I'm great!

1945
01:13:37,250 --> 01:13:39,553
You are great.

1946
01:13:39,586 --> 01:13:41,855
[Anna]
<i>Things weren't going well.</i>

1947
01:13:41,888 --> 01:13:43,624
Melody, stop!

1948
01:13:43,657 --> 01:13:44,758
Stop!

1949
01:13:44,791 --> 01:13:45,826
Stop it!

1950
01:13:45,859 --> 01:13:46,793
Calm down!

1951
01:13:51,565 --> 01:13:52,532
What?

1952
01:13:55,969 --> 01:13:58,137
Mom?

1953
01:13:59,339 --> 01:14:00,807
Is everything okay?

1954
01:14:01,842 --> 01:14:02,876
Just busy.

1955
01:14:02,909 --> 01:14:05,412
Did you find any investors yet?

1956
01:14:05,445 --> 01:14:07,514
Still working on it,
but they are out there.

1957
01:14:07,547 --> 01:14:08,682
And you're not doing
the other thing?

1958
01:14:08,715 --> 01:14:11,284
I said I wouldn't,
and I'm not, okay?

1959
01:14:11,318 --> 01:14:13,787
It's tough times
for everyone right now,

1960
01:14:13,820 --> 01:14:15,255
but we'll be fine, okay?

1961
01:14:15,288 --> 01:14:16,690
Do not worry.

1962
01:14:19,926 --> 01:14:21,828
[♪♪]

1963
01:14:26,366 --> 01:14:28,635
[Owen] "Sugar Ladies"?

1964
01:14:28,669 --> 01:14:29,936
What's this?

1965
01:14:29,970 --> 01:14:31,938
Investment opportunity.

1966
01:14:31,972 --> 01:14:32,973
For who?

1967
01:14:33,006 --> 01:14:34,941
Me.

1968
01:14:34,975 --> 01:14:36,643
You're kidding.

1969
01:14:36,677 --> 01:14:37,210
Why not?

1970
01:14:37,244 --> 01:14:38,945
You're better than this.

1971
01:14:38,979 --> 01:14:40,580
[scoffs]

1972
01:14:40,614 --> 01:14:43,450
Not everyone grew up upstate
with both their parents

1973
01:14:43,483 --> 01:14:45,852
and graduated high school
and got to go to college.

1974
01:14:45,886 --> 01:14:48,588
Some of us got kicked out
and were on the streets at 15.

1975
01:14:48,622 --> 01:14:51,291
Some of us had to make a living
the best way we knew how

1976
01:14:51,324 --> 01:14:52,759
to provide for ourselves
and our kids

1977
01:14:52,793 --> 01:14:54,728
after our husbands
crash into a median

1978
01:14:54,761 --> 01:14:56,463
and get thrown
through a windshield.

1979
01:14:56,496 --> 01:14:57,196
Whoa.
Where is this coming from?

1980
01:15:00,701 --> 01:15:02,602
Sorry.

1981
01:15:02,636 --> 01:15:05,305
[Anna] <i>Online matchmaking...
interactive, exclusive.</i>

1982
01:15:05,338 --> 01:15:07,641
<i>A premier dating site
for men and women.</i>

1983
01:15:07,674 --> 01:15:10,477
<i>All I needed
was $2 million in seed money.</i>

1984
01:15:10,510 --> 01:15:12,979
<i>And the best part?
Totally legal.</i>

1985
01:15:13,013 --> 01:15:14,614
<i>If I played my cards right,</i>

1986
01:15:14,648 --> 01:15:16,349
<i>Mia would never know
I broke my promise.</i>

1987
01:15:16,383 --> 01:15:17,751
<i>I called Arthur</i>

1988
01:15:17,784 --> 01:15:19,486
<i>and he arranged for us to meet
with a pair of investors.</i>

1989
01:15:19,519 --> 01:15:21,621
My business has always been

1990
01:15:21,655 --> 01:15:23,356
about catering
to the most exclusive clients.

1991
01:15:23,390 --> 01:15:25,492
As Arthur can tell you,

1992
01:15:25,525 --> 01:15:27,661
I turned a profit
with my first business

1993
01:15:27,694 --> 01:15:28,795
within the first two months,

1994
01:15:28,829 --> 01:15:31,031
and I expect
I can do even better here.

1995
01:15:31,064 --> 01:15:32,999
We like it.

1996
01:15:33,033 --> 01:15:35,635
A lot.

1997
01:15:40,407 --> 01:15:42,709
They better be legit, Arthur.

1998
01:15:42,743 --> 01:15:44,044
- They are.
- Well, you need to be sure

1999
01:15:44,077 --> 01:15:45,278
because I don't
want to be knee-deep

2000
01:15:45,312 --> 01:15:46,613
in Russian hooker drug money.

2001
01:15:46,646 --> 01:15:48,949
My kids are counting on me
not to keep messing up.

2002
01:15:48,982 --> 01:15:50,317
I know that.
You don't think I know that?

2003
01:15:50,350 --> 01:15:52,786
Your kids
are like my kids, Anna.

2004
01:15:54,454 --> 01:15:55,589
Look. Look.

2005
01:15:55,622 --> 01:15:56,156
We got a 10:00 a.m.
at the bank tomorrow

2006
01:15:56,189 --> 01:15:58,425
to transfer the funds.

2007
01:15:58,458 --> 01:15:59,960
These guys are the real deal.

2008
01:15:59,993 --> 01:16:01,928
I promise.

2009
01:16:01,962 --> 01:16:02,230
I...

2010
01:16:02,262 --> 01:16:03,430
What?

2011
01:16:03,463 --> 01:16:05,065
What is up with you lately, Art?

2012
01:16:05,098 --> 01:16:06,833
Nothing. No.

2013
01:16:06,867 --> 01:16:09,002
It's just everything.
It's a lot.

2014
01:16:09,035 --> 01:16:10,437
Yeah. Uh...

2015
01:16:10,470 --> 01:16:11,738
This is gonna work.

2016
01:16:11,772 --> 01:16:12,405
It's legit.
We're gonna be fine.

2017
01:16:12,439 --> 01:16:14,407
We better be

2018
01:16:14,441 --> 01:16:15,375
or it's your ass.

2019
01:16:15,408 --> 01:16:16,409
I know.

2020
01:16:17,410 --> 01:16:18,812
See you tomorrow.

2021
01:16:24,417 --> 01:16:26,019
[Anna]
<i>When I woke up that morning,</i>

2022
01:16:26,052 --> 01:16:27,320
<i>I knew something was wrong,</i>

2023
01:16:27,354 --> 01:16:31,792
<i>but I couldn't quite
put my finger on what it was.</i>

2024
01:16:31,825 --> 01:16:32,926
[sighs heavily]

2025
01:16:32,959 --> 01:16:33,994
You look nice.

2026
01:16:34,027 --> 01:16:35,028
Thank you.

2027
01:16:35,061 --> 01:16:36,029
And you'll be back in time
for the meet, right?

2028
01:16:36,062 --> 01:16:38,899
Absolutely. Should be back
before noon, okay?

2029
01:16:38,932 --> 01:16:39,432
I love you.

2030
01:16:39,466 --> 01:16:41,902
And I love you, too.

2031
01:16:41,935 --> 01:16:43,937
Ooh! Learn something
today, okay?

2032
01:16:43,970 --> 01:16:44,971
Okay.

2033
01:16:45,005 --> 01:16:46,106
[Anna chuckles]

2034
01:16:46,139 --> 01:16:47,307
- Bye.
- Bye.

2035
01:16:56,483 --> 01:16:58,852
[Anna]
<i>No one showed at the bank,</i>

2036
01:16:58,885 --> 01:17:00,453
<i>not even Arthur,</i>

2037
01:17:00,487 --> 01:17:01,822
<i>who wasn't answering my calls.</i>

2038
01:17:04,457 --> 01:17:08,461
[♪♪]

2039
01:17:18,705 --> 01:17:21,808
We can do this the easy way
or the hard way.

2040
01:17:21,842 --> 01:17:22,909
Help!

2041
01:17:22,943 --> 01:17:24,878
Somebody help!
I'm being kidnapped!

2042
01:17:27,747 --> 01:17:29,115
Somebody!

2043
01:17:34,421 --> 01:17:35,589
[Anna] <i>I thought this was it...</i>

2044
01:17:35,622 --> 01:17:36,723
<i>my last day on Earth.</i>

2045
01:17:36,756 --> 01:17:39,426
<i>I prayed my kids
would be okay without me.</i>

2046
01:17:39,459 --> 01:17:41,995
<i>But I wasn't going
without a fight.</i>

2047
01:17:45,198 --> 01:17:47,634
<i>I didn't know where I was,</i>

2048
01:17:47,667 --> 01:17:49,135
<i>where they'd taken me.</i>

2049
01:17:49,169 --> 01:17:50,570
<i>Was this it?</i>

2050
01:17:50,604 --> 01:17:52,072
<i>A bullet
to the back of the head</i>

2051
01:17:52,105 --> 01:17:52,372
<i>and then nothing?</i>

2052
01:17:54,208 --> 01:17:56,910
Sit down! Sit down.

2053
01:18:04,751 --> 01:18:06,519
Well, you're a giant pain
in my ass.

2054
01:18:07,954 --> 01:18:09,489
[♪♪]

2055
01:18:13,927 --> 01:18:15,395
[sighs]

2056
01:18:16,997 --> 01:18:18,965
Like I said
a thousand times already,

2057
01:18:18,999 --> 01:18:20,200
I don't know
what you're talking about.

2058
01:18:20,234 --> 01:18:21,201
I want to speak to my lawyer

2059
01:18:21,235 --> 01:18:24,504
and then I want
to get the hell out of here.

2060
01:18:24,537 --> 01:18:25,438
My kid has a meet at 5:00.

2061
01:18:25,472 --> 01:18:27,208
About your lawyer.

2062
01:18:27,241 --> 01:18:28,808
What about him?

2063
01:18:28,842 --> 01:18:30,510
We've already spoken to him.

2064
01:18:30,543 --> 01:18:33,079
We've... been speaking to him.

2065
01:18:33,113 --> 01:18:33,880
For months now.

2066
01:18:33,914 --> 01:18:35,515
And a woman named Melody.
Get it?

2067
01:18:40,086 --> 01:18:41,121
Art?

2068
01:18:41,154 --> 01:18:42,555
Yes.

2069
01:18:44,157 --> 01:18:46,059
[Anna] <i>I'd gotten sloppy,</i>

2070
01:18:46,092 --> 01:18:48,229
<i>right when
I had almost gone straight.</i>

2071
01:18:48,262 --> 01:18:49,397
<i>He was family...</i>

2072
01:18:49,429 --> 01:18:52,098
<i>the first person
who had ever believed in me.</i>

2073
01:18:52,132 --> 01:18:53,533
<i>I think he'd been trying
